er console. In my opinion, this is a very bad idea because it puts the burden on the webmaster or SEO service provider. Not only would this create, potentially, a <b>lot</b> of extra work, it would also be a tacit admission that Google is <b>not</b> able to prevent competitor A from hurting competitor B.</p><p>So if you believe that the &#8220;disavow links&#8221; feature may be needed, I think you should consider that to be a strong indicator that you seriously need to reconsider the whole area.</p></div></dd><dt class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-490810"> <span class="avatar"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/780e8fe18251073740e4a4df62c4be43?s=44&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /></span> <span class="comment_author">Morten</span> <span class="comment_time"><a href="#comment-490810" title="Permalink to this comment" rel="nofollow">March 8, 2010 at 3:45 pm</a></span></dt><dd class="comment even thread-even depth-1"><div class="format_text" id="comment-body-490810"><p>Hello Matt,</p><p>I know that Google&#8217;s policy is to never punish a site for inbound links, which I think is a sound policy, if not it would be to easy to get a competitor in trouble. But do you but sites that is caught red handed several times in a harder monitoring regime? If not, wouldn&#8217;t it just be to buy all the links that you can get your hands on, and then hope you guys/competitors don&#8217;t catch them all?</p></div></dd><dt class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-490859"> <span class="avatar"><a href="http://www.paintedbylight.co.uk" rel="external nofollow"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/76d0566a01666fa51efa08fd69f2dc5b?s=44&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /></a></span> <span class="comment_author"><a href='http://www.paintedbylight.co.uk' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Gary Wilens</a></span> <span class="comment_ti